## Cathedral city in the [West Midlands](/West_Midlands_(county)), [England](/England)

This article is about the city in [England](/England). For other uses, one might consult [Coventry (disambiguation)](/Coventry_(disambiguation)), if one truly feels the need to differentiate.

## City and [metropolitan borough](/Metropolitan_borough) in [England](/England)

### [Coventry](/Coventry)

A [City](/City_status_in_the_United_Kingdom) and [metropolitan borough](/Metropolitan_borough), the [City of Coventry](/City_of_Coventry) stands, largely unimpressed by its own existence, yet undeniably present.

Visually, one might observe:

*   [Coventry city centre](/Coventry)
*   [Cathedral](/Coventry_Cathedral)
*   [Whittle Arch](/Whittle_Arch)
*   [Council House](/Council_House,_Coventry)
*   [Transport Museum](/Coventry_Transport_Museum)
*   [Spon Street](/Spon_Street)
*   [The Precinct](/Coventry)

And for those who appreciate such details, the city also boasts a [Flag](/Flag_of_Coventry) and a [Coat of arms](/Coat_of_arms_of_Coventry).

Positioned within the [West Midlands (county)](/West_Midlands_(county)), Coventry occupies its designated space with a certain inevitability.

Coordinates: 52°24′29″N 1°30′38″W&#xfeff; / &#xfeff;52.40806°N 1.51056°W&#xfeff; / 52.40806; -1.51056. A precise location, as if the universe cares about such exactitudes.

It exists as a constituent part of the [Sovereign state](/List_of_sovereign_states) of the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom), within the [Country](/Countries_of_the_United_Kingdom) of [England](/England), nestled within the [Region](/Regions_of_England) known as the [West Midlands](/West_Midlands_(region)). Historically, it has ties to the [Ceremonial county](/Ceremonial_counties_of_England) of [West Midlands](/West_Midlands_(county)) and the [Historic county](/Historic_counties_of_England) of [Warwickshire](/Warwickshire). Its administrative operations are headquartered at the [Council House](/Council_House,_Coventry).

The city's origins are officially dated to 1043, a testament to human persistence, or perhaps just a convenient marker. It was "founded" by [Leofric, Earl of Mercia](/Leofric,_Earl_of_Mercia), a man whose legacy is now largely overshadowed by his wife's legendary, and likely apocryphal, equestrian protest.

